===message:Very good.  I liked your answer.  The South was scared about losing its ability to live off of the work of people that they did not have to pay.  You continue to offer good insight with your statement that a non-partisan solution would have been impossible, due to the South's disagreement based on the idea of states' rights.  The north also was concerned with the idea of state's rights.  They felt that the south's representatives had done them wrong on several issues.  They were also worried about the security of their jobs when free labor is so abundant, thus their reason for not wanting the spread of slavery to go on.  I agree highly with argument.  Any other comments?  What lead the south to believe that they were losing their rights as states? 
